---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Home">
  <section class="hero">
    <h1>The Workbench</h1>
    <p>Small software projects around data, coordination, and practical AI.</p>
    <p>This is a place for projects that are useful enough to explain properly. Some are live products. Some are learning projects. All of them are built around the same idea: keep the system understandable, make the work traceable, and avoid making things more complicated than they need to be.</p>
    <p><strong>By Adam Ojrzynski</strong></p>
  </section>

  <section class="section card card-feature wide-section">
    <p class="label">LIVE PRODUCT</p>
    <h2>ReadyRoll</h2>
    <p>A lightweight scheduling board for groups that meet regularly.</p>
    <p>ReadyRoll helps recurring groups keep track of availability across a shared date range, without making everyone create an account. A host creates a board, shares a link, people mark when they can attend, and the group can see the best upcoming dates without digging through chat.</p>
    <div class="meta">
      <div><strong>Status:</strong> Live product</div>
      <div><strong>Stack:</strong> Next.js, TypeScript, Tailwind, Supabase, Vercel</div>
      <div><strong>Features:</strong> Discord bot integration</div>
    </div>
    <p><a class="link-arrow" href="/readyroll/">Read about ReadyRoll →</a></p>
  </section>

  <section class="section card card-feature wide-section">
    <p class="label">AGENTS SUITE</p>
    <h2>Agents Suite</h2>
    <p>A growing suite of practical data agents built to understand agent architecture from the ground up.</p>
    <p>The suite starts with simple local Python agents that do recognisable data work: profiling datasets, reconciling records, and drafting data dictionaries. The aim is to learn where deterministic logic, review loops, and LLM support each belong.</p>
    <div class="meta">
      <div><strong>Type:</strong> Python CLI agents</div>
      <div><strong>Approach:</strong> Deterministic checks, traceable reports</div>
      <div><strong>Output:</strong> Optional LLM polish</div>
    </div>
    <div class="progression-pills" aria-label="Agents suite progression">
      <span>Deterministic CLI</span><span>Hybrid local + LLM</span><span>Framework agents</span><span>Multi-agent workflows</span><span>Capstone coordinator</span>
    </div>
    <p><a class="link-arrow" href="/agents/">Explore the suite →</a></p>
  </section>

  <section class="section card card-future prose">
    <p class="label">ON THE BENCH</p>
    <h2>Future work</h2>
    <p>This site will grow slowly. New projects will be added when they are mature enough to explain clearly and useful enough to sit alongside the main work.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="section wide-section">
    <div class="section-heading"><h2>Working Principles</h2></div>
    <div class="principles-grid">
      <article class="principle-item"><h3>Useful before impressive</h3><p>Build what solves real problems, not what sounds clever.</p></article>
      <article class="principle-item"><h3>Deterministic where possible</h3><p>Prefer predictable logic over probabilistic outputs when you can.</p></article>
      <article class="principle-item"><h3>LLMs as support, not source of truth</h3><p>Use AI for polish and suggestions, not as the primary decision maker.</p></article>
      <article class="principle-item"><h3>Clear traces, reports, and documentation</h3><p>Make the work visible so others can follow and verify it.</p></article>
      <article class="principle-item"><h3>Small systems that are easy to inspect</h3><p>Keep projects simple enough to understand completely.</p></article>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
